post_text:
Hello! The City of Quincy is in the process of developing a Master Parks Plan and a Non-motorized (bicycle/pedestrian) Transportation Plan. Over the next few months, the city will be working to develop a list of improvements to parks, bicycle routes, and sidewalks to accomplish in the near future.

In order to make this plan successful, they need to hear from you. Please take the short survey and let them know what you want to see in Quincy‚Äôs parks!

Take the survey here. (https://www.surveygizmo.com/s3/5708086/QuincyPTS)

Please visit the Master Parks Plan Page on their website for more information and to stay up-to-date about this process. (https://www.quincywashington.us/275/Master-Park-Plan)

If you have any questions, please contact:
Russ Harrington
509-787-3523
rharrington@quincywashington.us

Chris Overdorf
509-866-3265 ext. 286
Chris.overdorf@scjalliance.com

post_text:
The Quincy School District is looking for a Payroll /HR Assistant to join our team!
The Payroll /HR Assistant will process and coordinate payroll/HR services for the district. Responsibilities include meeting with new employees, verifying payroll/HR information, updating payroll/HR records, processing employee leave, entering information in payroll software, reconciling payroll, and maintaining knowledge of laws, procedures, and negotiated agreements that apply to payroll/HR. Maintaining confidentiality is a must for this position.

For a complete job description and qualifications please visit https://www2.ncrdc.wa-k12.net/scripts/cgiip.exe/WService=wquincys71/rapplmnu03.w

#nowhiring #jointheqsdteam #quincy #payroll #hrassistant #quincy #job

Once again, this is not a social gathering, participants should remain in their cars, pass by and return to their regularly scheduled physical distancing. Go Jacks!

shared_text:
Quincy Lady Jacks Wrestling
February 15 at 7:11 PM ¬∑

Quincy Lady Jacks gave it their all today. As a team, the girls placed 12th out of 49 teams. Duckie finished as the Regional Champion in the 155 Lb bracket, with pins all the way through. However, victory is not only measured by a final score. Brenda, Kim and Gladys finished out their high school career this weekend, with Brenda claiming 6th place honors. These Seniors contributed a ton to our program with consistent work ethic and great team spirit. Collectively, this team worked through injuries, took chances, learned new things, and grew as athletes, teammates, competitors, and young women. Shout out to Brenda Salgado, Xochitl Tafoya and Juana Giron for earning multiple wins at this tournament. Special thanks to those that made the trip to support these athletes, and especially to Colonial Market owner Les Albright for bringing the girls flowers to honor their accomplishments. Duckie will represent Quincy next week at the Tacoma Dome. Most of these girls will be back next year, tougher than ever. Seniors, thank you for the legacy you are leaving. Go Jacks!! üíö

#tbt Can you believe the entire Quincy student body used to fit in one school? Pictured, around the 1940s about 40 students in the current Ancient Lakes building that was once the original Quincy High School.
That building was built in 1938 originally as a Works Progress Administration federal program, as part of Franklin Delano Roosevelt New Deal Program after the Great Depression. Thank you to our friends @QuincyValleyHistoricalSociety for sharing these photos! #QHS #quincy #growth #qvhs

On October 2, the Quincy School District will be participating in ‚ÄúTaste of Washington Day,‚Äù sponsored by WSDA Farm to School, the Washington School Nutrition Association and Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction Child Nutrition. Taste of Washington Day is an annual celebration of Washington grown foods served in school meals during the fall harvest season. On October 2nd we will be serving locally grown apples and pears in the salad bar for both breakfast and lunch. Locally grown peppers, onions and cabbage will also be incorporated into the recipes that we will be serving at the Quincy Middle School and Quincy High School.

We are excited to serve our students with produce right from our ‚Äúbackyard!‚Äù

shared_text:
NAC Architecture
September 18, 2019 at 11:38 AM ¬∑

A big congratulations to Quincy School District on the opening of a brand new high school this fall! The district's sustained dedication has allowed Quincy to dream big, seeking the best opportunities available to the community‚Äôs youth, now and for generations to come. Read on to learn more about NAC's intentional design:

Quincy High School‚Äôs image expresses the robust agricultural economy and community while responding to the expanding technology opportunities in the region. Like the agricultural structures in the adjacent fields, the massing of the high school is simple and rectangular. Primary exterior materials include masonry and metal panels‚Äîcommon in the construction of agricultural buildings‚Äîexpressed with refined and sophisticated detailing and hinting at a high-tech aesthetic. On the interior, iconic shapes and forms of Quincy‚Äôs agricultural landscape have been used to create a dynamic visual language that encompasses the school‚Äôs visual environment. Both interior and exterior design celebrate the region‚Äôs physical and culture identity.

Quincy Police Department - WA
August 27, 2019 at 10:44 AM ¬∑

Back to School means we have some safety reminders for our drivers...

Please, please, pretty please, pay attention to school buses if you are approaching one, even from the opposite direction. When in doubt, stop until you see the bus moving again & make sure kids aren't crossing the street. Here's a great diagram to clear up any confusion.

On another note, if you get a chance to walk by the new Quincy High School (it feels different than just driving by) or any of the other schools, it's a pretty awesome feeling to know our community pulled together & made this happen. Way to go, Quincy! üëè

post_text: Congratulations to George Elementary‚Äôs Carole Leibelt, the 2019 Washington State PSE Member of the Year!
shared_text:
Public School Employees of Washington
August 3, 2019 at 8:10 PM ¬∑

We are proud to announce that our 2019 Education Support Professional of the Year is Carol Leibelt from PSE Quincy Chapter!

A custodian and PSE member for 27 years, Carol currently serves as her chapter‚Äôs treasurer and is a union advocate who supports and works hard for members.

On Thanksgiving 2018, she helped provide a place of shelter following the serious bus accident on I-90 near George that involved 56 marching band members from the University of Washington. This March, she was awarded the Red Cross Hometown Hero Award for her actions. Carol has also been named School Employee of the Year four times in her district and Custodian of the Year twice. This June, she represented PSE in Washington, D.C. as our 2019 recipient of the RISE (Recognizing Inspirational School Employees) Award.

Congratulations, Carol! Thank you for all you do for our union and for Washington's students.
